        <header>
            <h1>Evaporation Driven Self-Assembly</h1>
            <p>Evaporating the solvent from a colloidal particle dispersion provides a straightforward and effective method for creating two- or three-dimensional arrangements of colloids on solid surfaces. The drying of particle-laden droplets, polymers, drug molecules, or other micronutrients is a process commonly used in various industries, including printing, coating, spray drying, and the delivery of active ingredients.</p>
        </header>

        <section id="patterns">
            <h2>Pattern Formation</h2>
            <p>The drying of particle-laden drops on solid surfaces can generate a variety of particle organizations, such as:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Coffee-ring where particle concentration at the edge is higher,</li>
                <li>Uniform deposit with consistent particle density,</li>
                <li>Central or dome-like deposit with more particles at the center.</li>
            </ul>
